{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.04,0.16,0.01,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"304"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"2467"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1366"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-week-old girl presents to the Orthopaedic outpatient clinic for follow-up of developmental dysplasia of the hip. She was diagnosed as a newborn after a positive Ortolani test. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has been managed in a Pavlik harness since diagnosis. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to assess treatment response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hip ultrasound","Hip magnetic resonance imaging","Plain radiograph of the hip","Computed tomography of the hip","Clinical examination alone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of appropriate imaging selection based on patient age in developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH). In infants under four months of age, the hip joint is predominantly cartilaginous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation as it can effectively visualise cartilaginous structures and assess hip position and acetabular development. It provides real-time dynamic assessment without radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip magnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary at this stage. While it can provide detailed imaging of soft tissues, it is primarily reserved for post-surgical assessment and requires sedation in infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E of the hip has limited utility in infants under four months as the cartilaginous structures are not well visualised. Radiographs become useful after four months when ossification progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E of the hip involves unnecessary radiation exposure and is not appropriate for visualising cartilaginous structures. It may have a role in complex cases requiring surgical planning in older children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical examination alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for monitoring treatment response. While regular clinical examination remains important, imaging is necessary to objectively assess hip position and acetabular development during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of DDH requires regular monitoring to ensure appropriate hip development. Early detection and treatment with devices such as the Pavlik harness have significantly improved outcomes. If untreated, DDH can lead to gait abnormalities, leg length discrepancy, and early osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the imaging modality of choice for developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) in infants under four months due to cartilaginous hip structures","Plain radiographs become useful for developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) assessment after four months when ossification occurs","Risk factors for developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) include family history, breech position, and oligohydramnios"],"references":["Agarwal A, Gupta N. Risk factors and diagnosis of developmental dysplasia of hip in children. Journal of Clinical Orthopaedics and Trauma. 2012;3(1):10-14. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25983450/","Desai A, Martus J, Schoenecker J, Kan J. Spica MRI after closed reduction for developmental dysplasia of the hip. Pediatric Radiology. 2011;41(4):525-529. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21279341/","McEvoy A, Paton RW. Ultrasound compared with radiographic assessment in developmental dysplasia of the hip. J R Coll Surg Edinb. 1997 Aug;42(4):254-5. PMID: 9276562. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9276562/","Marks DS, Clegg J, al-Chalabi AN. Routine ultrasound screening for neonatal hip instability. Can it abolish late-presenting congenital dislocation of the hip? J Bone Joint Surg Br. 1994 Jul;76(4):534-8. PMID: 8027134. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8027134/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T19:05:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T19:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"379"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduatin